title: Grateful Dead Live at Veterans' Memorial Coliseum on 1984-04-23
lineage: Cassette (Nakamichi DR-1/Dolby B) -> Sound Devices 744T (24bit/96k) -> Adobe Audition v3 -> Samplitude Professional v11.03 -> FLAC/16
description:
Set 1

Jack Straw, Sugaree, Cassidy, Dupree's Diamond Blues, Hell In A Bucket-> Might As Well

Set 2

Iko Iko, Lost Sailor-> Saint Of Circumstance-> Uncle John's Band-> Only A Fool-> Drums-> Spanish Jam-> Truckin'-> Black Peter-> Around & Around-> Good Lovin', E: Day Job

reviews.review_text:
Wake & Bake Give this Lost Sailor/St. a listen.  The vocals are suppressed, there are drop-outs, the cymbals are too high, Brent might as well have been 5 different keyboardists (god I loved him!), there are tons of flaws.  Just tune it out a little and...

It's an architectural wonder.  From about 5-8m it's like standing on a mountaintop watching the loose ends on p-branes intersect.  Love their interpretations of the Barlow fantasies.  They nail the jam in St. to boot.  It's a lovely mix;  the light-through-winebottle variety.

One other note.  You hear Brent whispering lyrics at some point I forgot where.  Sounds like someone is sitting beside you mumbling.  He often did that and you hear it in places where they didn't kill his mic, particulary on '82-86.  Did I mention I loved him?  Lol.

Not Bad Relatively standard, Jerry sounding a little rough (Black Peter).
No significant highlights

gorgeous fun fun fun 
tasty jack straw, and saint of circumstance 
hell yes

Advent of the 6 song first set I was at this show. I, along with the whole section of people around me, were quite vocally shocked and disappointed by the six song first set. Both sets normally had 9 songs up until around 1984.

I remember some guy saying that the band knew the first set was a disappointment, and “say they will make it up in the second set”. Umm, the guy hadn’t moved from his seat the whole time… so yea.

But as a person who found Bob’s slide playing painful… this was the very rare first set without one of those Bob slide songs (CC Rider, Little Red Rooster, Minglewood Blues etc.). A small victory.

Listening back, Jack Straw has great energy. Jerry flubs the opening lyric of Sugaree, but it is played well.

More than anything, picking out and listening/attending these non-illustrious random Monday/Tuesday/Wednesday shows, reminds me that being in the Grateful Dead was, often, a job like any other. Some days are great, some days are ordinary, and some days aren’t great. But you show up, and by showing up, it’s a win.

This is one of those latter shows. We all showed up and did our best.
